 about potential improvements based on common optimization techniques applied within deep learning architectures while preserving all other aspects mentioned above.:


**Potential Modifications:**



* **Batch Normalization**: Introduce Batch Norm layers after each convolution operation (excepting those at layer `FC`). This helps stabilize gradients during training improving overall model generalization ability.<br>   <a href="reference">Reference</ a>. <b>(Estimated Time Consumption Increase)**




 * Use PyTorch's built -in ``torch._jit`` tracing functionality coupled wtih quantization strategies like Quantization Aware Training (`QAT`) discussed here:< br><ref url='qat'>Quantized Neural Networks via Model Parallelism Techniques Applied To Convolutional LSTM Architectures With Attention Mechanisms </ ref>, enabling efficient hardware deployment onto edge devices.( Estimated time consumption decrease due reduced network complexity )





## Conclusion : While implementing both batch normalization alongside QAt holds promise, evaluating their effectiveness requires further experimentation beyond scope currently possible given limited information. Nonetheless it remains an avenue worth exploring moving forwards towards optimizing resource utilization across various platforms







